    description: 'Embryonic and fetal development from conception to term',
    content: {
      concept: `# Fetal Development & Embryology

## Overview

Understanding fetal development is fundamental to fetal medicine. The process spans from fertilization through organogenesis to fetal maturation.

## Stages of Development

### Pre-embryonic Period (Weeks 1-2)

**Week 1: Fertilization to Implantation**
- **Day 0**: Fertilization in ampulla of fallopian tube
- **Day 1-3**: Cleavage divisions → morula (16 cells)
- **Day 4-5**: Blastocyst formation (inner cell mass + trophoblast)
- **Day 6-7**: Implantation begins (hatching from zona pellucida)

**Week 2: Bilaminar Disc**
- Trophoblast differentiates into:
  - **Cytotrophoblast** (inner, mitotically active)
  - **Syncytiotrophoblast** (outer, produces hCG)
- Inner cell mass forms bilaminar disc:
  - **Epiblast** (future embryo)
  - **Hypoblast** (future yolk sac)

> 💎 **High Yield**: hCG is produced by syncytiotrophoblast, detectable by day 8-10

### Embryonic Period (Weeks 3-8)

**Week 3: Gastrulation**
- Primitive streak forms
- Three germ layers established:
  - **Ectoderm**: Skin, CNS, neural crest
  - **Mesoderm**: Muscle, bone, cardiovascular, kidneys, gonads
  - **Endoderm**: GI tract, liver, pancreas, lungs

| Germ Layer | Derivatives |
|------------|-------------|
| Ectoderm | Brain, spinal cord, peripheral nerves, skin, hair, nails, eyes, ears |
| Mesoderm | Heart, blood vessels, skeleton, muscles, kidneys, gonads |
| Endoderm | GI epithelium, liver, pancreas, respiratory epithelium, thyroid, bladder |

**Week 4: Neurulation & Folding**
- Neural tube closes (day 21-28)
- **Cranial neuropore**: Closes day 25 (failure → anencephaly)
- **Caudal neuropore**: Closes day 27 (failure → spina bifida)
- Heart begins beating (day 22)
- Embryonic folding creates tubular structure

> 📌 **Critical Period**: Folic acid must be present BEFORE conception to prevent NTDs

**Week 5-8: Organogenesis**

| Week | Key Developments |
|------|------------------|
| 5 | Upper limb buds, heart chambers forming, lens placodes |
| 6 | Lower limb buds, hand plates, primitive gut |
| 7 | Digital rays (fingers), eyelids forming, intestines in umbilical cord |
| 8 | Distinct fingers/toes, external genitalia begin, intestines return to abdomen |

> 💎 **High Yield**: By end of week 8, all organ systems are present in rudimentary form

### Fetal Period (Weeks 9-40)

**First Trimester (Weeks 9-12)**
- Rapid growth and differentiation
- **Week 9**: Fetal period begins, CRL ~25 mm
- **Week 10**: External genitalia begin to differentiate
- **Week 11**: Urine production begins
- **Week 12**: External genitalia distinguishable, ossification centers appear

**Second Trimester (Weeks 13-28)**

| Week | CRL/Weight | Key Developments |
|------|------------|------------------|
| 14 | 8 cm | Sex distinguishable externally |
| 16 | 12 cm / 100g | Quickening possible (multiparas) |
| 18 | 14 cm / 200g | Vernix caseosa appears |
| 20 | 16 cm / 300g | Lanugo covers body, quickening (primiparas) |
| 24 | 21 cm / 600g | Surfactant production begins, viability threshold |
| 28 | 25 cm / 1000g | Eyes open, can regulate temperature |

> 💎 **Viability**: 24 weeks is the threshold; 50% survival at tertiary centers

**Third Trimester (Weeks 29-40)**

| Week | Weight | Key Developments |
|------|--------|------------------|
| 32 | 1800g | Lanugo begins to disappear, nails reach fingertips |
| 34 | 2100g | Surfactant adequate, less need for NICU |
| 36 | 2500g | Fat deposition, body becomes rounder |
| 38 | 3000g | Firm cartilage in ears and nose |
| 40 | 3400g | Term, ready for extrauterine life |

## Teratogenic Periods

### Critical vs. Sensitive Periods

- **All-or-none period** (weeks 1-2): Teratogen causes death or no effect
- **Embryonic period** (weeks 3-8): Maximum teratogenic risk (organogenesis)
- **Fetal period** (weeks 9-40): Growth/functional defects, less structural malformation

### Organ-Specific Critical Periods

| Organ System | Critical Period | Common Defects |
|--------------|-----------------|----------------|
| CNS | Week 3-16 (continues) | NTDs, microcephaly, intellectual disability |
| Heart | Week 3-8 | Septal defects, conotruncal anomalies |
| Limbs | Week 4-8 | Limb reduction, phocomelia |
| Eyes | Week 4-9 | Microphthalmia, cataracts |
| Ears | Week 4-12 | Deafness |
| Palate | Week 6-9 | Cleft palate |
| External genitalia | Week 7-12 | Ambiguous genitalia |

## Placental Development

### Formation
- **Week 3**: Primary villi (trophoblast only)
- **Week 4**: Secondary villi (mesoderm core)
- **Week 5**: Tertiary villi (blood vessels present)

### Mature Placenta (Term)
- Weight: 450-600g (1/6 of fetal weight)
- Diameter: 15-20 cm
- Thickness: 2-3 cm
- 15-20 cotyledons

### Functions
1. **Gas exchange**: O₂ to fetus, CO₂ to mother
2. **Nutrition**: Glucose, amino acids, fatty acids
3. **Excretion**: Waste products to maternal circulation
4. **Hormone production**: hCG, hPL, progesterone, estrogens
5. **Immunological barrier**: Transfers IgG (passive immunity)

> 💎 **High Yield**: Only IgG crosses placenta (passive immunity); peaks at 32-34 weeks

## Amniotic Fluid

### Production
- **Early pregnancy**: Transudation from fetal skin, placenta
- **Second half**: Mainly fetal urine (500-700 mL/day at term)

### Removal
- Fetal swallowing (500 mL/day)
- Intramembranous absorption

### Normal Volume
- **20 weeks**: 400 mL
- **34 weeks**: 1000 mL (peak)
- **40 weeks**: 800 mL
- **Post-term**: Declines

### Clinical Significance

| Condition | AFI | Causes |
|-----------|-----|--------|
| Oligohydramnios | <5 cm | IUGR, renal agenesis, PROM, post-term |
| Polyhydramnios | >25 cm | GDM, hydrops, GI obstruction, anencephaly |

> 📌 **Potter Sequence**: Oligohydramnios → pulmonary hypoplasia, limb deformities, facial compression`,
