    name: 'First Trimester Screening',
    slug: 'first-trimester-screening',
    description: 'Combined test, NT measurement, and early aneuploidy screening',
    content: {
      concept: `# First Trimester Screening

## Overview

First trimester screening (11-13+6 weeks) combines ultrasound markers with biochemistry to calculate aneuploidy risk. It is a **screening test** (not diagnostic).

## Combined Test Components

### 1. Nuchal Translucency (NT)

**Definition**: Subcutaneous fluid collection at the back of the fetal neck

**Measurement Criteria**:
- Gestational age: 11+0 to 13+6 weeks
- CRL: 45-84 mm
- Mid-sagittal plane, fetal profile visible
- Measure widest thickness, perpendicular to fetal long axis
- Calipers placed ON the lines (inner-to-inner)

**Normal Values**:
- 95th percentile increases with CRL
- At CRL 45 mm: 95th percentile = 2.1 mm
- At CRL 84 mm: 95th percentile = 2.7 mm

> 💎 **High Yield**: NT >3.5 mm = high risk for aneuploidy AND cardiac defects (offer echo regardless of karyotype)

**Causes of Increased NT**:

| Category | Examples |
|----------|----------|
| Chromosomal | Trisomy 21, 18, 13; Turner syndrome; Triploidy |
| Cardiac defects | Septal defects, coarctation, hypoplastic left heart |
| Genetic syndromes | Noonan syndrome, Smith-Lemli-Opitz |
| Other | Diaphragmatic hernia, skeletal dysplasia |

### 2. Additional Ultrasound Markers

**Nasal Bone**
- Absent in 60-70% of T21 fetuses
- Absent in only 1-3% of euploid fetuses
- Adds to detection rate when combined with NT

**Ductus Venosus**
- Absent or reversed a-wave suggests aneuploidy or cardiac defect
- Normal: forward flow throughout cardiac cycle

**Tricuspid Regurgitation**
- Present in 55% of T21 (vs 1% euploid)
- Measured in apical four-chamber view

### 3. Biochemical Markers

**PAPP-A (Pregnancy-Associated Plasma Protein A)**
- Produced by syncytiotrophoblast
- LOW in T21, T18, T13

**Free β-hCG (or total hCG)**
- HIGH in T21
- LOW in T18, T13

| Condition | PAPP-A | β-hCG |
|-----------|--------|-------|
| Trisomy 21 (Down) | ↓ | ↑ |
| Trisomy 18 (Edwards) | ↓ | ↓ |
| Trisomy 13 (Patau) | ↓ | ↓ |
| Triploidy (type I) | ↓ | ↑↑ |
| Triploidy (type II) | ↓↓ | ↓ |

> 📌 **Remember**: "Down = Up" (β-hCG is UP in Down syndrome)

### Combined Test Performance

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Detection rate for T21 | 85-90% |
| False positive rate | 5% |
| Optimal timing | 11-13+6 weeks |

## Risk Calculation

### Method
Risk = Background risk × Likelihood ratios (NT + biochemistry)

**Background Risk Factors**:
- Maternal age (main factor)
- Previous affected pregnancy
- Gestational age at delivery

### Risk Thresholds

| Risk Level | Risk | Action |
|------------|------|--------|
| High risk | >1:100 | Offer CVS/Amniocentesis |
| Intermediate | 1:100 - 1:1000 | Offer NIPT or invasive testing |
| Low risk | <1:1000 | Routine care |

## Additional First Trimester Findings

### Early Anomaly Scan Components
- **Crown-rump length** (dating)
- **Chorionicity** in multiple pregnancy
- **Uterus and adnexa**
- **Fetal number and viability**

### First Trimester Anomalies Detectable

| Anomaly | Detection Rate |
|---------|----------------|
| Anencephaly | >95% |
| Major abdominal wall defects | >95% |
| Major limb abnormalities | 50-60% |
| Megacystis (bladder >7mm) | >90% |

> 💎 **High Yield**: Anencephaly diagnosed by absent calvarium - 100% lethal, offer termination

## Quality Assurance

### FMF Certification
- Nuchal Translucency must be measured by certified operators
- Annual audit of measurements
- Standardized technique ensures accuracy

### Reporting
- Report should include:
  - NT measurement (mm and MoM)
  - Biochemistry (PAPP-A, β-hCG as MoM)
  - Combined risk for T21, T18, T13
  - Recommendation based on risk`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Combined test = NT + PAPP-A + β-hCG + maternal age (11-13+6 weeks)',
