  // =============================================================================
  // NON-INVASIVE PRENATAL TESTING (NIPT)
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'nipt',
    subjectId: 'obgyn',
    subspecialtyId: 'obgyn-fetal-medicine',
    name: 'Non-Invasive Prenatal Testing (NIPT)',
    slug: 'nipt',
    description: 'Cell-free DNA screening for aneuploidy',
    content: {
      concept: `# Non-Invasive Prenatal Testing (NIPT)

## Overview

NIPT analyzes cell-free fetal DNA (cffDNA) circulating in maternal blood to screen for chromosomal abnormalities. It is the most sensitive **screening test** available but is NOT diagnostic.

## Biology of Cell-Free DNA

### Source
- Primarily from placental trophoblast (not fetal cells)
- Released by apoptosis of syncytiotrophoblast
- Therefore detects **placental** genetics (usually same as fetus)

### Characteristics
- Detectable from ~4-5 weeks
- Sufficient for testing from **10 weeks**
- Fetal fraction: 3-13% of total cfDNA (increases with GA)
- Half-life: ~16 minutes (cleared rapidly after delivery)

> 💎 **High Yield**: NIPT tests PLACENTAL DNA, not fetal DNA directly. This explains discordant results.

### Minimum Fetal Fraction
- Most labs require **>4%** fetal fraction
- Low fetal fraction causes:
  - Early gestational age
  - High maternal BMI (adipose tissue releases maternal cfDNA)
  - Aneuploidy (especially T13, T18)

## What NIPT Screens For

### Standard Panel
| Condition | Detection Rate | False Positive Rate |
|-----------|---------------|---------------------|
| Trisomy 21 (Down) | >99% | 0.04% |
| Trisomy 18 (Edwards) | 97-99% | 0.04% |
| Trisomy 13 (Patau) | 87-99% | 0.04% |
| Sex chromosomes | 90-96% | 0.3% |

### Extended Panels (Available in Some Labs)
- Microdeletions (22q11.2, 1p36, etc.)
- Other aneuploidies (T16, T22)
- Genome-wide abnormalities

> 📌 **Important**: Microdeletion screening has LOWER positive predictive value - more false positives

## Positive Predictive Value (PPV)

NIPT has excellent sensitivity but PPV depends on **prior risk**:

| Population | Prior Risk T21 | PPV for Positive NIPT |
|------------|---------------|----------------------|
| High-risk (age 40) | 1:100 | 91% |
| Average-risk (age 30) | 1:1000 | 50% |
| Low-risk (age 25) | 1:1500 | 33% |

> 💎 **Critical Point**: Positive NIPT in low-risk population = ~50% chance of TRUE positive. ALWAYS confirm with invasive testing.

## Causes of False Results

### False Positives
1. **Confined placental mosaicism (CPM)** - Most common
   - Placenta aneuploid, fetus euploid
   - Occurs in 1-2% of CVS

2. **Vanishing twin**
   - Demised twin's placental DNA still present
   - May persist for weeks

3. **Maternal chromosome abnormality**
   - Turner mosaicism
   - Maternal malignancy (rare)

### False Negatives
1. Low fetal fraction
2. True fetal mosaicism (low-level)
3. Laboratory error

### No-Call Results
- Insufficient fetal fraction
- Repeat draw in 1-2 weeks
- Fetal fraction <4% associated with higher aneuploidy risk

## Indications for NIPT

### ACOG/SMFM Guidelines
- **Universal option**: Can be offered to ALL pregnant women
- **Particularly useful when**:
  - Advanced maternal age (≥35)
  - Abnormal serum screening
  - Ultrasound finding suggesting aneuploidy
  - History of previous aneuploidy
  - Known parental chromosomal abnormality

### When NOT to Use NIPT Alone
- Multiple gestations (limited data, lower detection)
- High suspicion of structural anomaly (need invasive)
- Known maternal chromosomal abnormality

## NIPT vs Traditional Screening

| Feature | Combined Test | NIPT |
|---------|--------------|------|
| Timing | 11-13+6 weeks | ≥10 weeks |
| Detection T21 | 85-90% | >99% |
| False positive rate | 5% | 0.04% |
| Cost | Lower | Higher |
| Additional info | NT, early anatomy | None |
| Turnaround | Same day-1 week | 1-2 weeks |

## Counseling Points

### Pre-test Counseling
1. NIPT is a **screening test** - not diagnostic
2. Positive result requires **confirmation** with CVS/amnio
3. Cannot detect all genetic conditions
4. May reveal incidental findings (sex chromosome abnormalities)
5. Possibility of no-result (need redraw or invasive testing)

### Post-test (Positive Result)
1. Do not make decisions based on NIPT alone
2. Offer confirmatory invasive testing
3. Genetic counseling
4. PPV varies by prior risk and condition
5. Support and time for decision-making`,
      keyPoints: [
        'NIPT detects placental cfDNA, not fetal DNA directly',
        'Detection rate >99% for T21, but still a SCREENING test',
        'Positive NIPT requires confirmation with CVS/amniocentesis',
        'PPV depends on prior risk - lower in low-risk women',
        'Common false positive cause: confined placental mosaicism'
      ],
      examPrep: {
        summary: `**NIPT - Quick Review**

🔬 **Source**: Placental cell-free DNA (not fetal cells)

⏰ **Timing**: ≥10 weeks (need adequate fetal fraction)

📊 **Detection T21**: >99% (best screening test available)

⚠️ **False Positive Rate**: 0.04% (but PPV varies!)

🎯 **Remember**: SCREENING test - always confirm positive with invasive testing

❌ **False positives from**: CPM, vanishing twin, maternal abnormality`,
        mnemonics: [
          'NIPT = Not Invasive, Placenta Tested',
          'CPM = Common cause of Positive that is Misleading',
          'Low fetal fraction: "Fat mothers, Early testing, Aneuploid babies"'
        ],
        highYield: [
          'Minimum fetal fraction needed: >4%',
          'High BMI reduces fetal fraction (more maternal cfDNA)',
          'Positive NIPT in average-risk woman: ~50% PPV',
          'Confined placental mosaicism is the most common cause of false positive',
          'No-call result may indicate higher aneuploidy risk'
        ],
        commonMCQs: [
          'Source of cell-free DNA in NIPT: Placental trophoblast',
          'Detection rate of NIPT for T21: >99%',
          'Most common cause of false positive NIPT: Confined placental mosaicism',
          'NIPT is a: Screening test (requires confirmation if positive)'
        ]
      },
      textbookRefs: [
        { textbook: 'Williams Obstetrics', edition: '26th', chapter: 'Chapter 14', chapterTitle: 'Prenatal Diagnosis' }
      ],
      retrievalCards: [
        { id: 'nipt-1', question: 'What is the source of cell-free DNA analyzed in NIPT?', answer: 'Placental trophoblast cells (not fetal cells) - released by apoptosis', difficulty: 2 },
        { id: 'nipt-2', question: 'What is the detection rate of NIPT for Trisomy 21?', answer: '>99%', difficulty: 1 },
        { id: 'nipt-3', question: 'What is the most common cause of false positive NIPT?', answer: 'Confined placental mosaicism (CPM) - placenta aneuploid, fetus euploid', difficulty: 2 },
        { id: 'nipt-4', question: 'Why does high maternal BMI affect NIPT accuracy?', answer: 'Adipose tissue releases more maternal cfDNA, reducing fetal fraction below acceptable levels', difficulty: 3 },
        { id: 'nipt-5', question: 'What should be done after a positive NIPT result?', answer: 'Confirm with invasive diagnostic testing (CVS or amniocentesis) - NIPT is a screening test', difficulty: 2 },
        { id: 'nipt-6', question: 'What is the earliest gestational age for NIPT?', answer: '10 weeks (need adequate fetal fraction, typically >4%)', difficulty: 2 }
      ],
      cases: [
        {
          id: 'nipt-case-1',
          title: 'Positive NIPT in Low-Risk Woman',
          presentation: 'A healthy 28-year-old G1P0 has NIPT showing high risk for Trisomy 21. Her first trimester combined test was low risk (1:5000). She had no ultrasound abnormalities.',
          questions: [
