  // =============================================================================
  // IUGR (INTRAUTERINE GROWTH RESTRICTION)
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'iugr',
    subjectId: 'obgyn',
    subspecialtyId: 'obgyn-fetal-medicine',
    name: 'Intrauterine Growth Restriction',
    slug: 'iugr',
    description: 'IUGR types, Doppler assessment, and management',
    content: {
      concept: `# Intrauterine Growth Restriction (IUGR)

## Definitions

**Small for Gestational Age (SGA)**: EFW or AC <10th percentile
- May be constitutionally small (normal) or pathologically small (IUGR)

**Fetal Growth Restriction (FGR/IUGR)**: Failure to reach genetic growth potential
- Pathological process with risk of adverse outcomes
- Suggested by abnormal Dopplers, oligohydramnios, or growth trajectory

> 💎 **High Yield**: Not all SGA babies are growth restricted; not all FGR babies are SGA

## Types of IUGR

### Symmetric IUGR (20-30%)

**Characteristics**
- All measurements proportionally small (HC, AC, FL)
- Head:Abdominal ratio normal
- Early onset (first trimester)

**Causes**
- Chromosomal abnormalities (T21, T18, T13)
- Congenital infections (TORCH - especially CMV, Rubella)
- Fetal structural anomalies
- Severe early-onset placental insufficiency
- Teratogens

### Asymmetric IUGR (70-80%)

**Characteristics**
- AC small, HC relatively preserved ("head-sparing")
- Elevated HC/AC ratio (>1 after 32 weeks abnormal)
- Late onset (second/third trimester)

**Causes**
- Placental insufficiency (most common)
  - Preeclampsia
  - Chronic hypertension
  - Antiphospholipid syndrome
  - Maternal vascular disease
- Maternal factors
  - Malnutrition
  - Smoking, substance abuse
  - High altitude

> 📌 **Brain-sparing**: Fetus redistributes blood flow to brain at expense of abdominal organs

## Doppler Assessment

### Umbilical Artery Doppler

**Normal**: Low-resistance flow (forward diastolic flow)

**Stages of Deterioration**:

| Stage | Finding | Significance |
|-------|---------|--------------|
| 1 | High S/D ratio, elevated PI | Early placental dysfunction |
| 2 | Absent end-diastolic flow (AEDF) | Severe dysfunction, 50% delivery within 1 week |
| 3 | Reversed end-diastolic flow (REDF) | Critical, high mortality if undelivered |

> 💎 **High Yield**: AEDF/REDF = Immediate hospitalization, steroids if preterm, delivery planning

### Middle Cerebral Artery (MCA)

**Normal**: High-resistance flow

**Brain-sparing (redistribution)**:
- MCA PI decreased (low-resistance)
- Increased blood flow to brain
- CPR <1 suggests redistribution

**MCA PSV**:
- Used to detect fetal anemia
- >1.5 MoM suggests anemia (Rhesus disease, infections)

### Cerebroplacental Ratio (CPR)

**Formula**: MCA PI / UA PI

**Interpretation**:
| CPR | Significance |
|-----|--------------|
| >1 | Normal |
| <1 | Brain-sparing/redistribution |
| <1 with abnormal UA | High risk, close surveillance |

### Ductus Venosus (DV)

**Normal**: Forward flow throughout cardiac cycle (positive a-wave)

**Abnormal**:
- Absent a-wave
- Reversed a-wave (most ominous)

> 💎 **High Yield**: Reversed DV a-wave = cardiac decompensation, imminent demise if undelivered

## Staging of IUGR (Delphi Classification)

### Early-onset FGR (<32 weeks)
| Stage | Criteria |
|-------|----------|
| Stage I | EFW <3rd centile OR AC <3rd centile OR UA PI >95th |
| Stage II | AEDF in UA OR Reversed DV a-wave |
| Stage III | REDF in UA |
| Stage IV | Abnormal CTG OR stillbirth |

### Late-onset FGR (≥32 weeks)
| Stage | Criteria |
|-------|----------|
| Stage I | EFW <3rd centile OR AC <3rd centile |
| Stage II | EFW <10th + abnormal CPR (<5th) or UA PI >95th |
| Stage III | As early-onset |
| Stage IV | As early-onset |

## Management

### Antepartum Surveillance

**Monitoring Schedule**:
| Doppler Status | Frequency |
|----------------|-----------|
| Normal UA | Weekly Doppler, biweekly CTG |
| Elevated UA PI | Twice weekly Doppler, daily CTG |
| AEDF | Daily/twice daily CTG, deliver by 32-34 weeks |
| REDF | Continuous CTG, deliver by 30-32 weeks |
| Abnormal DV | Immediate delivery consideration |

### Timing of Delivery

| Gestational Age | Condition | Action |
|-----------------|-----------|--------|
| <26 weeks | REDF/abnormal DV | Individual decision, high mortality |
| 26-28 weeks | REDF/abnormal DV | Steroids, deliver 48-72h if stable |
| 28-32 weeks | AEDF | Steroids, deliver 32-34 weeks |
| 32-34 weeks | AEDF | Deliver (consider steroids if none) |
| >34 weeks | Any IUGR | Deliver by 37-38 weeks |
| >37 weeks | SGA | Deliver |

### Antenatal Steroids
- Give if <34 weeks and delivery anticipated
- Betamethasone 12 mg IM x 2 doses, 24h apart
- Dexamethasone 6 mg IM x 4 doses, 12h apart

### Magnesium for Neuroprotection
- Give if <32 weeks and delivery anticipated
- 4g IV loading dose

### Mode of Delivery
- Vaginal delivery acceptable if:
  - Reassuring CTG
  - Cephalic presentation
  - No severe REDF/DV changes
- Low threshold for cesarean due to poor reserve

## Prognosis

### Short-term Risks
- Hypoglycemia
- Hypothermia
- Polycythemia
- Hyperbilirubinemia
- Necrotizing enterocolitis

### Long-term Risks
- Neurodevelopmental delay
- Metabolic syndrome (Barker hypothesis)
- Cardiovascular disease
- Type 2 diabetes`,
      keyPoints: [
