  {
    id: 'fetal-anomalies',
    subjectId: 'obgyn',
    subspecialtyId: 'obgyn-fetal-medicine',
    name: 'Fetal Structural Anomalies',
    slug: 'fetal-anomalies',
    description: 'Neural tube defects, cardiac anomalies, and renal abnormalities',
    content: {
      concept: `# Fetal Structural Anomalies

## Neural Tube Defects (NTDs)

### Types

| Type | Description | Prognosis |
|------|-------------|-----------|
| **Anencephaly** | Absence of calvarium and brain | Lethal, 100% mortality |
| **Encephalocele** | Brain herniation through skull defect | Variable, depends on size/content |
| **Spina bifida** | Vertebral arch defect ± meningeal/neural herniation | Variable, location-dependent |

### Anencephaly
- Most common lethal NTD
- Diagnosed in first trimester (absent skull vault)
- **Ultrasound**: "Frog-eye" appearance, absent cranium above orbits
- Associated with polyhydramnios (impaired swallowing)
- Termination or comfort care at birth

### Spina Bifida

**Types**:
- **Spina bifida occulta**: Vertebral defect only, skin intact
- **Meningocele**: Meninges herniate, neural tissue in canal
- **Myelomeningocele**: Neural tissue herniates (most common open type)

**Ultrasound Signs**:
- **Lemon sign**: Scalloped frontal bones
- **Banana sign**: Curved cerebellum (Chiari II)
- **Ventriculomegaly**: Common
- **Spinal defect**: Splaying of posterior elements

**Associated Findings**:
- Chiari II malformation (99% of open cases)
- Hydrocephalus (85-90% require shunt)
- Clubfoot
- Bladder dysfunction

**Management**:
1. Karyotype (amniocentesis)
2. MRI for detailed assessment
3. Multidisciplinary counseling
4. Options: Termination, postnatal surgery, fetal surgery (MOMS trial)

> 💎 **High Yield**: MOMS trial showed fetal surgery reduces shunt need and improves motor outcomes, but increases preterm delivery

### Prevention
- Folic acid 400 mcg preconception
- High-dose 5 mg for: previous NTD, antiepileptics, diabetes

## Cardiac Anomalies

### Overview
- Incidence: 8/1000 live births
- Leading cause of death from congenital anomalies
- 4-chamber view alone detects only 40-50%

### Common Cardiac Defects

| Defect | Prevalence | Ultrasound Finding |
|--------|------------|-------------------|
| VSD | Most common (25-30%) | Dropout in ventricular septum |
| AVSD | 3-5% | Common AV valve, primum ASD |
| Hypoplastic left heart | 1-2% | Small LV, aorta; normal appearing 4-chamber possible |
| Tetralogy of Fallot | 3-5% | Overriding aorta, VSD, small PA |
| Transposition | 3% | Parallel great vessels (not crossing) |
| Coarctation | 5-8% | Size discrepancy in 3VV, may be subtle |

### Screening

**Risk Factors for CHD**:
- Previous CHD child
- Maternal diabetes
- Maternal CHD
- Teratogen exposure (alcohol, phenytoin, lithium)
- Increased NT (>3.5 mm)
- Abnormal serum screening

**Fetal Echocardiography Indications**:
- NT >3.5 mm (regardless of karyotype)
- Family history of CHD
- Maternal diabetes (pregestational)
- Teratogen exposure
- Extracardiac anomaly on scan
- Abnormal 4-chamber view

### Prognosis by Lesion

| Lesion | Prognosis |
|--------|-----------|
| Isolated VSD | Often closes spontaneously |
| AVSD | Surgical repair, good outcomes |
| HLHS | Requires staged surgery (Norwood), 50-70% 5-yr survival |
| TGA | Arterial switch operation, good outcomes |
| ToF | Surgical repair, good outcomes |

## Renal Anomalies

### Classification

**Structural Anomalies**:
- Renal agenesis (unilateral/bilateral)
- Multicystic dysplastic kidney (MCDK)
- Polycystic kidney disease
- Hydronephrosis/pyelectasis
- Duplex collecting system

### Bilateral Renal Agenesis

**Features**:
- **Severe oligohydramnios** (no fetal urine)
- Absent kidneys on ultrasound
- Absent bladder filling
- **Potter sequence**: Pulmonary hypoplasia, limb deformities, facial features

**Prognosis**: Lethal - offer termination

### Multicystic Dysplastic Kidney (MCDK)

**Ultrasound**:
- Multiple non-communicating cysts
- No normal renal parenchyma
- Absent normal pelvis

**Management**:
- Unilateral: Usually benign, involutes postnatally
- Bilateral: Lethal (no urine production)
- Follow-up for hypertension

### Hydronephrosis (Pyelectasis)

**Definition by APD (Anteroposterior diameter of renal pelvis)**:

| Trimester | Mild | Moderate | Severe |
|-----------|------|----------|--------|
| 2nd trimester | 4-7 mm | 7-10 mm | >10 mm |
| 3rd trimester | 7-9 mm | 9-15 mm | >15 mm |

**Causes**:
- PUJ obstruction (most common)
- VUJ obstruction
- Posterior urethral valves (males)
- Vesicoureteric reflux
- Duplex kidney with obstructed upper pole

> 💎 **High Yield**: Mild isolated pyelectasis often resolves; severe bilateral with oligohydramnios suggests obstruction

### Posterior Urethral Valves (PUV)

**Features**:
- **Male fetus** only
- Dilated posterior urethra ("keyhole" sign)
- Bilateral hydroureteronephrosis
- Thick-walled, distended bladder
- Oligohydramnios

**Management**:
- Amnioinfusion for lung development
- Fetal therapy: Vesicoamniotic shunt
- Postnatal: Valve ablation

### Autosomal Recessive Polycystic Kidney Disease (ARPKD)

**Features**:
- Enlarged, echogenic kidneys
- Oligohydramnios
- Associated hepatic fibrosis
- High recurrence risk (25%)

**Prognosis**: Variable; severe cases lethal; survivors may need transplant

## Abdominal Wall Defects

### Gastroschisis

**Features**:
- Defect usually RIGHT of umbilical cord
- Bowel freely floating in amniotic fluid
- No covering membrane
- Small defect (<4 cm)
- Usually isolated (normal karyotype)

**Associations**:
- Young maternal age
- Smoking, vasoconstriction
- NOT associated with chromosomal abnormalities

**Management**:
- Serial growth scans (risk of IUGR)
- Monitor bowel dilation
- Delivery at tertiary center
- Mode: Vaginal usually acceptable

### Omphalocele

**Features**:
- Central defect at umbilical cord insertion
- Contents covered by membrane (peritoneum/amnion)
- May contain liver
- Variable size

**Associations**:
- Chromosomal abnormalities (30-50%)
- Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome
- Cardiac defects

**Management**:
- Karyotype (amniocentesis)
- Detailed anomaly scan
- Fetal echocardiography
- Counseling depends on contents and associations`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Anencephaly: 100% lethal, diagnosed by absent calvarium',
        'Spina bifida: Lemon + Banana signs on USS; MOMS trial shows fetal surgery benefit',
        '4-chamber view detects only 40-50% of CHD - outflow tracts essential',
        'Bilateral renal agenesis = Potter sequence = lethal',
        'Gastroschisis: isolated, right of cord; Omphalocele: associated with aneuploidy, has membrane'
      ],
