  // =============================================================================
  // MULTIPLE PREGNANCY (TWINS)
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'multiple-pregnancy',
    subjectId: 'obgyn',
    subspecialtyId: 'obgyn-fetal-medicine',
    name: 'Multiple Pregnancy & Twin Complications',
    slug: 'multiple-pregnancy',
    description: 'Chorionicity, TTTS, selective IUGR, and management of twins',
    content: {
      concept: `# Multiple Pregnancy & Twin Complications

## Types of Twins

### Dizygotic (DZ) Twins - 70%
- Two separate eggs fertilized by two sperm
- Always dichorionic diamniotic (DCDA)
- Genetically different (like siblings)
- Risk factors: Maternal age, ART, family history, race

### Monozygotic (MZ) Twins - 30%
- Single fertilized egg splits
- Chorionicity depends on timing of division:

| Timing of Split | Result | Frequency |
|-----------------|--------|-----------|
| Day 1-3 | Dichorionic Diamniotic (DCDA) | 25-30% |
| Day 4-8 | Monochorionic Diamniotic (MCDA) | 70-75% |
| Day 8-13 | Monochorionic Monoamniotic (MCMA) | 1-2% |
| Day >13 | Conjoined twins | Rare |

> 💎 **High Yield**: Later split = more shared structures = more complications

## Determining Chorionicity

### Optimal Timing
- **Best**: 11-14 weeks (most accurate)
- After 14 weeks: Membrane characteristics used

### Ultrasound Signs

| Sign | DCDA | MCDA |
|------|------|------|
| Separate placentas | Yes | Single or fused |
| Lambda sign (peak) | Present | Absent |
| T-sign | Absent | Present |
| Membrane thickness | Thick (>2mm) | Thin |
| Number of layers | 4 | 2 |
| Fetal sex | May differ | Same |

**Lambda (Twin Peak) Sign**: Triangular projection of placental tissue between membranes - indicates DCDA

**T-Sign**: Membranes meet placenta at 90° - indicates MCDA

> 📌 **Critical**: Chorionicity must be established in first trimester - determines entire management

## Risks of Multiple Pregnancy

### Maternal Complications
- Hyperemesis gravidarum (increased hCG)
- Gestational diabetes (increased hPL)
- Preeclampsia (3x risk)
- Anemia
- Cesarean delivery (>50%)
- Postpartum hemorrhage

### Fetal Complications
| Complication | DCDA | MCDA | MCMA |
|--------------|------|------|------|
| Preterm delivery | ↑ | ↑↑ | ↑↑↑ |
| IUGR | ↑ | ↑↑ | ↑↑ |
| Fetal loss | 2% | 12% | 50% (untreated) |
| Anomalies | ↑ | ↑↑ | ↑↑ |
| TTTS | No | 10-15% | No |
| Cord entanglement | No | No | High |

## Twin-to-Twin Transfusion Syndrome (TTTS)

### Pathophysiology
- Occurs only in **MCDA twins** (shared placenta with vascular anastomoses)
- Unbalanced blood flow through arteriovenous anastomoses
- **Donor twin**: Hypovolemic, anemic, oliguric → oligohydramnios, IUGR
- **Recipient twin**: Hypervolemic, polycythemic, polyuric → polyhydramnios, cardiac overload

### Diagnosis (Quintero Staging)

| Stage | Findings |
|-------|----------|
| I | Oligohydramnios (DVP <2cm) in donor + Polyhydramnios (DVP >8cm) in recipient |
| II | Absent bladder in donor |
| III | Abnormal Doppler: AEDF/REDF in UA, reversed DV a-wave, pulsatile UV |
| IV | Hydrops in one or both |
| V | Demise of one or both |

> 💎 **High Yield**: TTTS diagnostic criteria = Oligo-Poly sequence in MCDA twins (DVP <2cm donor, >8cm recipient)

### Management

**Conservative** (Stage I):
- Close surveillance (weekly ultrasound)
- May stabilize or regress

**Fetoscopic Laser Ablation** (Stage II-IV):
- Treatment of choice for stage II-IV before 26 weeks
- Laser coagulation of placental vascular anastomoses
- Survival: 80-90% at least one twin, 50-60% both twins

**Amnioreduction**:
- Alternative if laser not available
- Reduces polyhydramnios, prolongs pregnancy
- Inferior outcomes to laser

**Selective Feticide**:
- If one twin severely affected
- Cord occlusion (not intracardiac injection in MCDA)

## Selective Intrauterine Growth Restriction (sIUGR)

### Definition
- EFW discordance >25% in MCDA twins
- One twin <10th percentile

### Types (Based on UA Doppler of Smaller Twin)

| Type | UA Doppler | Prognosis |
|------|------------|-----------|
| Type I | Normal | Good, watch closely |
| Type II | Persistent AEDF/REDF | Poor, high mortality risk |
| Type III | Intermittent AEDF/REDF | Variable, unpredictable |

### Management
- Serial surveillance
- Type II/III: Consider laser ablation or selective feticide
- Delivery timing based on Doppler deterioration

## Monoamniotic Twins (MCMA)

### Risks
- **Cord entanglement**: 50-70% risk
- Very high mortality (historically 50-70%)
- Preterm delivery

### Management
- Intensive surveillance from 24 weeks
- Consider daily CTG from 26-28 weeks
- **Delivery at 32-34 weeks** by cesarean
- Steroid administration at 26-28 weeks

## Twin Anemia-Polycythemia Sequence (TAPS)

### Features
- Large difference in Hb between twins (>8 g/dL)
- Without amniotic fluid discordance
- Due to chronic, slow transfusion

### Diagnosis
- MCA PSV discordant (>1.5 MoM in anemic twin, <0.8 MoM in polycythemic)
- Can occur spontaneously or post-laser TTTS

### Management
- Laser ablation of residual anastomoses
- Intrauterine transfusion
- Expectant with close monitoring

## Management of Twin Pregnancy

### Surveillance Schedule

| Chorionicity | Surveillance |
|--------------|--------------|
| DCDA | Scans at 20, 28, 32, 36 weeks |
| MCDA | Scans every 2 weeks from 16 weeks |
| MCMA | Weekly from 24 weeks, daily CTG from 26-28 |

### Timing of Delivery

| Chorionicity | Uncomplicated | Complicated |
|--------------|---------------|-------------|
| DCDA | 37-38 weeks | As indicated |
| MCDA | 36-37 weeks | Earlier if TTTS, sIUGR |
| MCMA | 32-34 weeks | - |

### Mode of Delivery
- **Twin A cephalic**: Vaginal delivery considered
- **Twin A non-cephalic**: Cesarean
- **MCMA**: Always cesarean (cord entanglement risk)`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Chorionicity must be established in first trimester',
        'Lambda sign = DCDA; T-sign = MCDA',
