  // =============================================================================
  // HYDROPS FETALIS
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'hydrops-fetalis',
    subjectId: 'obgyn',
    subspecialtyId: 'obgyn-fetal-medicine',
    name: 'Hydrops Fetalis',
    slug: 'hydrops-fetalis',
    description: 'Immune and non-immune hydrops: causes, diagnosis, and management',
    content: {
      concept: `# Hydrops Fetalis

## Definition

Abnormal accumulation of fluid in **two or more** fetal body compartments:
- Skin edema (>5 mm)
- Ascites
- Pleural effusion
- Pericardial effusion

Often associated with polyhydramnios and placental edema.

## Classification

### Immune Hydrops (10-20%)
- Due to red cell alloimmunization
- Antibodies cross placenta → hemolysis → anemia → high-output cardiac failure

**Causes**:
- Rh (D) alloimmunization (most common immune cause)
- Anti-Kell (K1) antibodies
- Anti-c, anti-E, anti-Duffy

> 💎 **High Yield**: With universal RhoGAM prophylaxis, immune hydrops has declined dramatically

### Non-Immune Hydrops (80-90%)
- All causes not related to red cell alloimmunization
- More diverse and often more challenging to diagnose

**Categories of Non-Immune Hydrops**:

| Category | % | Examples |
|----------|---|----------|
| Cardiovascular | 20-25% | Structural CHD, arrhythmias, cardiomyopathy, AV malformations |
| Chromosomal | 10-15% | Turner syndrome (45,X), T21, T18, T13, triploidy |
| Hematologic | 10-15% | Parvovirus B19, alpha-thalassemia, G6PD deficiency |
| Thoracic | 5-10% | CPAM/CCAM, CDH, pleural effusion, chylothorax |
| Twin-related | 5-10% | TTTS, TAPS, TRAP sequence |
| Infections | 5-10% | Parvovirus B19, CMV, syphilis, toxoplasmosis |
| Urinary | 5% | Obstructive uropathy |
| Genetic syndromes | 5-10% | Noonan, multiple pterygium, storage diseases |
| Idiopathic | 15-25% | No cause found despite evaluation |

## Pathophysiology

### Common Pathway
1. **Anemia** → High-output cardiac failure (Rh disease, parvovirus)
2. **Cardiac dysfunction** → Low-output failure (CHD, arrhythmias, cardiomyopathy)
3. **Hypoproteinemia** → Decreased oncotic pressure (liver failure, lymphatic obstruction)
4. **Lymphatic obstruction** → Turner syndrome, storage diseases
5. **Vascular leak** → Infections, placental pathology

### Fluid Accumulation Sequence
- Often starts in one compartment
- Progresses to generalized hydrops
- Placental edema (>6 cm) and polyhydramnios common

## Diagnosis

### Ultrasound Features

**Fluid Collections**:
- Ascites: Fluid around bowel, in pelvis
- Pleural effusion: Fluid around lungs
- Pericardial effusion: Fluid around heart (>2 mm abnormal)
- Skin edema: >5 mm thickness

**Associated Findings**:
- Polyhydramnios (reduced swallowing, increased urine output)
- Placental edema (>6 cm thickness)
- Cardiomegaly

### Investigations

**Maternal**:
- Blood group and antibody screen (rule out immune)
- Kleihauer-Betke test (fetomat